d inhabited, was a hybrid product of architects’, planners’, and residents’ understandings of modernity. This volume identifies the “right to comfort” as an invention of the postwar period and suggests that the modern mass home played a vital role in shaping new expectations for well-being and happiness.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aArchitecture, DomesticzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aDwellingszFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aHousing policyzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aHousingzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / Contemporary (1945-).2bisacsh  aarchitects.  aarchitecture.  aart of living.  ademocracy.  ademocratization.  adesign textbook.  afrench history.  afrench home.  afrench society.  agenerational.  ahistory.  ahome decor.  ainterior design.  alife changes.  amodern home.  amodern mass home.  amodernity.  anation-building.  apolitical.  aproject of modernization.  arebuilding after the war.  aretrospective.  aright to comfort.  asocial engineering.  asociology.  asuburban.  avillage settings.  aww ii.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBerghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311099823840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782385882?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782385882423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782385882/original  a978-3-11-099823-8  Berghahn Books Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK